title: Remix Remix: Deluxe spool holder for XYZPrinting daVinci

description.text:
I wanted a spool holder for my daVinci that would still allow the top to open without having to cut anything. This was inspired by the other deluxe spool holders. You have to slide the top up to attach the brackets, but then you can slide it back down and there is plenty of clearance for it to open. The brackets have cutouts to accommodate spines on the daVinci. The overhang of the cutout is slanted so that supports are not needed.  
I use a plastic rod I found around the house for the axis, but I have included an axis similar to the one from the original remix. That should be printed horizontally with supports for greatest strength.  
Edit: I added a bracket called "SuperLeft" that will fit to the far left of the daVinci 1.0. You will need a different axis, but this would allow you to use a spool of any width. You could also use multiple spools (but I would use all 3 supports in that case).

title: Soporte ajustable del fin de carrera Z  -  Adjustable Z endstop holder

description.text:
Una idea simple y eficaz para ajustar con precisión la posición vertical del fin de carrera del eje Z.  
El fin de carrera se sujeta con una brida sobre un clip móvil, anclado en la varilla lisa del eje Z. La segunda pieza, que hace el papel de base, se apoya firmemente sobre el soporte del motor izquierdo del eje Z.  
El sistema de ajuste consiste en un tornillo M4, pasante en el clip móvil y roscado en la pieza de la base, y un muelle de compresión que mantiene la distancia correcta entre la pieza de la base y el clip móvil.

A simple and effective idea to finely adjust the vertical position of the endstop on the Z axis.  
The endstop is attached with a flange on a mobile clip, anchored in the Z axis smooth rod. The second part, which plays the base rol, rests firmly on the Z axis left motor mount.  
The adjusting system consists of a M4 screw, through the mobile clip and threaded into the base part, and a compression spring that maintains the correct distance between the base part and the movable clip.

description.text:
6-12-17, I just uploaded a new mod to the file, it is sculpted and mirrored and smoothed.  It is Buffalo 5 6-12...
This is a scan of a Buffalo skull (American Bison) that was done with a Microsoft Kinect for Windows and ReconstructmeQT software.  
I am uploading several versions of the files.  One is the full scan, the other is the skull and horns in separate files.  
I've uploaded OBJ files, STL files, and Makerware Thing files.

The all in one file is printed with support and two extra shells, be careful removing the support.  
I had hoped to make it a dual extruder print with black horns and a white skull, but Makerware does not allow support for dual extrusion projects.  So instead, I am printing the skull and then the horns in separate prints.  
You can load the skull and each horn file separately into your slicer, but don't resize them or move them until all three are load and all parts are selected.  That way you will be sure to have them aligned.  In Makerware, I did this, and they were mostly off screen as they come in life size.  With all 3 selected, I did a shrink to fit and then moved the group to the build platform and rotated as needed to get the flat bottom on the build plate.  The thing files are already set up this way.  
If you want to print in max size with the skull one color and the horns another, bring all 3 in, delete each horn, scale the skull, keeping track of what percent you use or the before and after dimensions so you can determine a scale percent.  Save the file for later use.  Undo the resize, undo the horn deletions, delete the skull, and scale the horns by the same percent the skull was scaled.  Save your horn file with a new name.  Now reopen the skull file, position on your build plate and slice it. Do the same with the horn file.

Hi all, this is a set of 2 beams that you can print on your printer to see if it prints the exact length you input into the printer.  
The square one to do both lengths at once, 100x100mm X and Y, this is useful if you have a measuring device that cannot measure lengths like 170mm.  
I have made the long one because most printers have a print range ranging from 175~200mm's of size on the printbed, and most calibration parts that I have found are either for making circles or are just a set length like 50mm or a 100mm's long. I wanted to get a more precise measurement, and you only get more precise when you add more length because when your printer isn't calibrated a 100% it wil be more visible with a longer piece.  
Anyway, this was for personal use, but I am willing to share.  
I hope it is of any use to someone.

A first pass attempt at printing the frame of a small, toy, rubber-band powered flapping flying machine. This small ornithopter is based on the tutorials I've seen for wooden ornithopters on Instructables, most particularly on the tutorial by Captain Molo http://www.instructables.com/id/Ornithopter/ Known Issues
Please note, this is WIP - mostly because I couldn't get it to reliably fly. It prints - it assembles - it flaps in your hands. But when I try to fly it, it manages only a few flaps before stalling. I suspect that wobbly axles are losing me most of the rubber-band power, but it could be anything at this point. I also suspect that massive weight savings could be made on future iterations of this ornithopter - the one I've uploaded here is SOLID. There is no flex, even when it's crashing nose first into the grass. There's fat to be trimmed here, for certain.

Print the following: 1x Ornithopter Body
2x Ornithopter Struts
2x Ornithopter Wings
1x Ornithopter Tail Many of these parts (the body and wing in particular) are right on the limit of printing size, and you may need to adjust the exact printing position to get it to fit. When you have the parts, you need to drill (or melt) holes in both ends of the struts, one end of the wings, and one though the bottom tab of the body. The last holes to drill, are into the tab at the corner of the tail (drill towards the center of the triangle) and a hole into the end of the body, facing the tail. Unfortunately, the uppermost pair of tabs isn't quite big enough to fit two holes for the wing axles, so you may be forced (as I was) to glue on small beads to hold the wing axles. I'm afraid the rest of the instructions are a bit involved for here - I recommend checking out the tutorial on Instructables and going along with that.

description.text:
In 2012, my daughter became a tissue donor, donating her heart valves after being stillborn at 39 weeks, 3 days. My wife and I are actively involved with organ donation awareness through Lifebanc, which is Northeast Ohio's Organ Donation Procurement Agency. I created this tile as part of a gift I am making for her birthday after a couple of unsuccessful searches for one. I used AutoCAD Inventor Pro and printed it on my MakerBot Replicator 5th Gen printer. The DonateLife2 file has a thinner solid section on the back. I didn't like the way it looked when I printed the first version (I thought it was a bit small), so I scaled it up 150% and it measured 1.5" square, which looked better.  
I added a picture of the finished product. I paused the print just before the letters started to take shape and used acrylic paint to fill in the blue and green sections.
For various small Dremel and Proxxon tools, we needed a box to keep it. So this is a gcode-only-example done at the cologne fablab "dingfabrik.de".

One DIN-A4 size 4mm plywood is cutted by the CNC-mill into 4 layers. Use a 3mm tool for drilling and cutting wood.
The 3 bottom layers need to be glued to the basic box.
A 12mm long M3 screw holds the top layer together with the basic box. Slide it to the top to open the box.
Finish.
For spheric tools, I just drilled a larger fitting into the box, so I needed no further changes at the gcode.

This is how you can covert your 2 stick tx into a single stick tx...
remember that every potentiometer is different so you need to change the dimensions of the cavity for the potentiometer.... and you need to check the diameter of the stick of the transmitter to the diameter of the hole in the module... the wires will pass through the cavity provided, see pictures for that....

https://3dwarehouse.sketchup.com/model.html?id=u073ab68b-cc69-43a6-9e6f-1bbc1e8bd337 Working and assembling video of the mechanism
http://goo.gl/dCqJjR

SketchUp (.skp) file for changing any dimension according to your potentiometer, can be downloaded from here
https://3dwarehouse.sketchup.com/model.html?id=u47782863-25f0-4398-9004-4a29ba207944 This time I designined a 3D printed module to hold the potentiometer in place over the Aileron and Elevator stick, The design is pretty simple, the rotor comes back in the center position, when released... the springs used in the actual gimbal from the transmitter are used here... This is how you can covert your 2 stick tx into a single stick tx... Print the Module, Link mentioned down below. You need to make some holes in the gimble itself, so that the wires can pass through, BUT DONT DAMAGE ANYTHING ELSE, For that take the gimble out of the transmitter.... Tear the gimbal, REMEMBER TO TAKE NOTE WHICH PART IS LOCATED WHERE, Easy way is to take pictures.... Assemble the gimbal again when the holes are drilled... Now you need to extend the wires from the rudder potentiometer, so that they can pass through the hole that you just made....use wire of same thickness if possible. Now remove the rudder potentiometer from the gimbal, take note of the order of the wires, REMEMBER THE ORIENTATION OF THE COLOURS... And remove the 2 springs which bring the stick back when released, those will be used later.... Place the potentiometer in the module that you printed, Center the potentiometer, before installing , remember that every potentiometer is different so you need to change the dimensions of the cavity for the potentiometer.... and you need to check the diameter of the stick of the transmitter to the diameter of the hole in the module... the wires will pass through the cavity provided, see pictures for that.... the springs will be hooked to the 2, "L" shaped brackets, If you broke those by mistake, like I did, use Small screws which come with the servos, See pictures for idea.... Before packing everything, just test it with the help of your plane that you are currently using, if the servo moves in the opposite direction to your input, then switch any 2 wires, ALWAYS SWITCH OUTSIDE WIRES, NEVER TOUCH THE WIRE WHICH IS IN THE MIDDLE! If eveything is WORKING, then PACK everything, if something is lose then use CA, DONT LET THE CA TO GO INSIDE THE POTENTIOMETER, BECAUSE THAT WILL DESTROY IT!

description.text:
A super compact band cam satbilizer that can
effectively suppress all rotational induced image unsharpnesses.

Full sized tripods are the best stabisisation method for cameras - no question. But when you're hiking or go to a party they are too heavy and bulky. Most people will think twice and only take a tripod with them if taking photos is the main objective. Also small tripods can't really replace full sized ones. Then there are rope stabilisatiors available but their stabilization effect is very limited. So with the current situation you often have to fall back to harsh and ugly flash light in party situations or you have to use high ISO values for beautiful dawn sceneries making the images unnecessary noisy.

In short it's an elaborate improvement to the rope stabilisator method.
(Refer to the images to better understand the following description.)
It's a stable H-shaped structure that screws onto the bottom of any camera.
This structure provides four eyelets as stabilization points.
Through the left two and right two eyelets runs each a wire loop with around 60cm circumference length.
(I prototyped with electric wire to attain low tensibility and high outer friction)
Those loops make the pitch choosable on the fly and more importantly stabilize the pitch.
Thereby vertical smearing in the resulting image is reduced.
On the bottom of each loop is a band (again with low tensibility) connected.
This is done via hooks and strap-tri-glides with eyelets.
The bands are length adjustable and form loops at their ends for the photogrphers feet to slip in.
Those two bands make the hight and roll adjustable and more importantly stabilize the roll.
Thereby circular smearing around the center of the resulting image is reduced.
The yaw instabilities and the assoziated horizontal image smearing must be compensated with the cameras native neck strap.
This is intended and must be noted in the "stabilisators" description - it's very important.

Slip into the shoe loops.
Take a wide but still comfortable stride.
Put the cameras neck strap around you.
Pull the camera forward and upward (you may move the loops to adjust pitch).
Don't pull too weak or to strong just comfortable and use both hands.
Take a THE photo. Handling of the prototype feels good but an overload protection turned out to be neccesary.
(Stepping on the bands while walking can break the eyelets.)
Performance was not yet quantified.

Compact & Lightweight.
 Rotation stabilisation on all axes.
Quickadjustable Pitch.
 Unobstrusive when mounted.
  • mount screw retention
  • insets for corc/felt/rubber
  • stiff design
  • optimal size for micro 4/3 cameras

title: Seed starter for AeroGarden 3 and rockwool cubes

description.text: Replacement tray to use your AeroGarden 3 hydroponic system with seed starter plugs.

This part replaces the top of the bowl in a AeroGarden 3 hydroponic kit. I've made two versions of the tray. One holds up to 16 Grodan 1.5" Rockwool cubes and for the other one, I was able to squeeze in 20.  You would germinate your seeds in 1.5" rockwool cubes, the way you would normally. After they have sprouted, transfer them to this starter tray. Don't try to sprout them using the AeroGarden Bio-Domes.   
The cubes are packed in pretty tightly so you can't keep them in the tray for very long or the roots will grow together.  I'm using this to grow starters that'll be transferred into zipgrow hydroponic towers but you could just as easily use it for soil destined plants.   
Notes:  
1) Keep all the squares filled with cubes (use empty rockwood cubes if you have to) so that light won't be able to get into the bowl below the plants.   
2) It was designed to exactly fit Grodan 1.5" rockwool plugs and probably will not work very well with anything that is not exactly that same shape and size.   
3) One of the holes is directly over the air pump hose so the cube for that hole doesn't quite fit right. It'll either sit up as compared to the rest or need to be made a little smaller.

description.text:
New! I added a flange to my filament guide, based on my tension nut, so spools with large hubs stay on track and I don't need to worry about the filament looping off the roll on a long unattended print job. The tension nut is tight enough that it doesn't need a screw to hold it in place though you can add one if you need it. The hole has a large fillet on both sides so the filament will pass through easily and the arm should accommodate various spools. You can add a small square of foam in front of it and push the filament through. The foam will clean off any loose dust or particles on the filament before it gets to your extruder. I use this and the corresponding tension nut (thing 737155) to reliably print my cameras on pinholeprinted.com.
https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:737155

Printed in ABS using 0.4mm nozzle at 0.25mm layer height with 25% infill.  You MUST generate support in your slicer for the flange.
